diagnoses.name: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body, including skin, joints, kidneys, heart, and brain. It can cause widespread inflammation and tissue damage in the affected organs.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid arthritis
diagnoses.description: Another autoimmune disease that primarily affects the joints but can also involve other tissues and organs, including the skin, kidneys, and heart.

diagnoses.name: Viral pericarditis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the pericardium, often due to a viral infection. This condition can lead to pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Uremic pericarditis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the pericardium associated with uremia, a serious complication of chronic kidney disease and acute kidney failure.

diagnoses.name: Infectious mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: Commonly caused by the Epstein-Barr virus, this condition can lead to the development of nephritis, pericarditis, and follicular hyperkeratosis.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that can affect multiple organs in the body, including the heart (leading to pericarditis) and kidneys (potentially leading to nephritis).

diagnoses.name: Mixed connective tissue disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disorder that has features of three other connective tissue diseases: lupus, scleroderma, and polymyositis. It may present with nephritis, pericarditis, and various skin changes.

diagnoses.name: Drug-induced lupus erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A lupus-like syndrome that is caused by certain prescription drugs. Symptoms are similar to those of systemic lupus erythematosus, including pericarditis and nephritis.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash. While primarily affecting skin and muscles, it can also have complications leading to pericarditis.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki disease
diagnoses.description: Primarily affects children. It causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body, including those of the heart. This can lead to pericarditis and an effusion, albeit less commonly associated with nephritis or the specific skin changes noted.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause hypersensitivity reactions, inflammation, and damage to various body systems.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout the body, leading to symptoms like hypersensitivity reactions, and possibly epistaxis.

diagnoses.name: Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing inflammation of the blood vessels in your nose, sinuses, throat, lungs, and kidneys, potentially causing epistaxis and problems in the urinary tract.

diagnoses.name: Urinary Tract Infection
diagnoses.description: An infection in any part of your urinary system, most commonly presenting with frequent, sometimes painful urination, and could lead to hypersensitivity in severe cases.

diagnoses.name: Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder
diagnoses.description: A chronic disorder in which a person has uncontrollable, reoccurring thoughts (obsessions) and behaviors (compulsions).

diagnoses.name: Allergic Rhinitis
diagnoses.description: An allergic response causing symptoms such as sneezing, itching, nasal congestion, and in severe cases possibly leading to epistaxis.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein Purpura
diagnoses.description: A disorder that causes the small blood vessels in your skin, joints, intestines, and kidneys to become inflamed and bleed, leading to a variety of symptoms including hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Immunodeficiency Disorders
diagnoses.description: Disorders that make it harder for your body to fight infections and other diseases, which may manifest through frequent infections like urinary tract infections.

diagnoses.name: Sinusitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation or swelling of the tissue lining the sinuses, leading to symptoms like congestion and possibly complicating with epistaxis.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood and bone marrow that can cause a wide range of symptoms, depending on the type, including hypersensitivity reactions, infections, and bleeding like epistaxis.

diagnoses: Squamous cell carcinoma of the head and neck

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: A disease involving abnormal collections of inflammatory cells that form lumps known as granulomas. The condition can affect the lymph nodes, eyes, and skin, leading to systemic symptoms including increased susceptibility to infection.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis. It typically affects the lungs but can also affect lymph nodes, eyes, skin, and other parts of the body, creating a wide range of symptoms including lymphadenitis and increased susceptibility to infections.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus/Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome is a spectrum of conditions caused by infection with the human immunodeficiency virus, leading to progressive failure of the immune system. It can cause lymphadenopathy, make the body more susceptible to infections including various forms of cysts and skin conditions like angiomata.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout your body. The disease can lead to numerous signs and symptoms that may seem unrelated at first, including mouth sores, eye inflammation, skin rashes and lesions, and even genital sores.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A group of blood cancers that develop in the lymphatic system. The two main types are Hodgkin lymphoma and non-Hodgkin lymphoma. Symptoms may include lymphadenopathy, increased susceptibility to infections, and systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Granulomatous Disease
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that affects the immune system's ability to function properly. It is characterized by the formation of granulomas, increased susceptibility to infections, and may include the development of cysts and abscesses.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease where the body's immune system becomes hyperactive and attacks normal, healthy tissue. Symptoms include inflammation, swelling, damage to joints, skin, kidneys, blood, the heart, and lungs, including lymphadenopathy and increased susceptibility to infections.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder characterized by the immune system attacking glands that produce tears and saliva. It often accompanies other immune system disorders, such as rheumatoid arthritis and lupus. Symptoms include dry eyes, which can feel irritated, and a greater vulnerability to infections.

diagnoses.name: Rosai-Dorfman Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder that causes an overproduction of histiocytes, a type of white blood cell. This leads to lymphadenopathy and sometimes lesions in the skin and soft tissues, resembling cysts or angiomata.

diagnoses.name: Ataxia Telangiectasia
diagnoses.description: A rare, genetic disorder that affects the nervous system, immune system, and other body systems. This condition is characterized by progressive difficulty with coordinating movements (ataxia) starting in early childhood and telangiectasias (angiomata) on the skin and eyes. Patients are very susceptible to infections and have an increased risk of developing lymphoma and leukemia.

diagnoses.details: Obsessive-compulsive behavior, which may affect dietary habits potentially influencing glycemic lability and appetite changes.
Glycemic lability and increased appetite are common symptoms. Stress and anxiety from conditions like OCD can impact blood sugar levels.
Increased appetite can lead to obesity, a risk factor for metabolic syndrome, which also includes disorders of glycemic control.
May explain hemorrhoids, which are a type of venous insufficiency, and could be exacerbated by increased body weight.
Could explain tinnitus. While not directly related to other symptoms, OCD stressors could potentially aggravate its manifestations.
Can be related to metabolic syndrome and obesity, indirectly linked to symptoms like increased appetite and potentially affecting hemorrhoidal conditions.
May manifest with obsessive-compulsive behaviors. Some people eat more due to depression, potentially explaining increased appetite. Depression is also a risk factor for obesity.
Though not directly related, anemia can be a complicating factor if hemorrhoids lead to significant blood loss. Increased appetite might occur if the body craves more nutrients.
Can cause increased appetite and affect metabolic rate, potentially linking to glycemic lability if weight gain occurs. Might also impact mood and contribute to depressive symptoms.
In women, PCOS can cause weight gain, lead to metabolic issues including glycemic lability, and may be associated with mood disorders.

diagnoses: Neurological conditions affecting the facial muscles

diagnoses.name: Blepharitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the eyelids which can cause symptoms like irritated, itchy eyes, and blepharospasm.

diagnoses.name: Dry Eye Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs when tears aren't able to provide adequate moisture, leading to irritated eyes.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes increased red blood cell production, leading to plethora.

diagnoses.name: Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD)
diagnoses.description: A mental disorder where people feel the need to check things repeatedly or have certain thoughts repeatedly (obsessive-compulsive behavior).

diagnoses.name: Meibomian Gland Dysfunction
diagnoses.description: A common eye condition that causes the eyelids to become inflamed and can lead to irritated eyes and blepharospasm.

diagnoses.name: Cystic Fibrosis
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that causes severe damage to the lungs and other organs due to thick and sticky mucus, leading to fibrosis.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An immune system disorder characterized by dry eyes and mouth, which could potentially correlate with irritated eyes.

diagnoses.name: Tourette Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A nervous system disorder involving repetitive movements or unwanted sounds, which can sometimes include obsessive-compulsive behavior.

diagnoses.name: Idiopathic Pulmonary Fibrosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic, progressive lung disease that causes scarring (fibrosis) of the lungs.

diagnoses.name: Blepharospasm
diagnoses.description: A condition causing involuntary tight closure of the eyelids.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: A condition in which blood lacks adequate healthy red blood cells, often caused by blood loss, insufficient iron intake, or other medical conditions. Iron deficiency can lead to symptoms like fatigue and can cause or exacerbate restless legs syndrome. It may also be associated with thrombocytosis (an increase in the number of platelets) in some cases.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition where the kidneys do not work as well as they should. It can lead to a buildup of waste products in the blood, causing symptoms like fatigue and restless legs syndrome. Chronic kidney disease can also result in thrombocytosis and affect the body's ability to regulate fluids, leading to conditions like vaginitis due to hormonal imbalances.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A metabolic disorder characterized by high blood sugar levels over a prolonged period. Diabetes can cause fatigue and lead to a higher risk of infections, including vaginitis. It can also contribute to the development of chronic kidney disease, which in turn can lead to symptoms like restless legs.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that primarily affects joints but can also involve other systems. Fatigue is a common symptom due to the body's ongoing inflammatory response. Restless legs syndrome has been reported in patients with RA, possibly due to systemic inflammation or secondary iron deficiency anemia. Thrombocytosis might also occur in the context of inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes the bone marrow to produce too many red blood cells. These excess cells thicken the blood, leading to symptoms such as fatigue and presyncope. Thrombocytosis is also common in polycythemia vera. Restless legs syndrome may occur due to altered blood flow.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones. Symptoms include fatigue, and the condition can also lead to menstrual changes or issues like vaginitis due to hormonal imbalances. Restless legs syndrome can be a related symptom as well.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that affects the central nervous system, leading to symptoms like fatigue. It can also cause neurological symptoms that mimic or cause restless legs syndrome. While vaginitis is not a direct symptom, the overall impact on health can predispose to such conditions.

diagnoses.name: Depressive Disorder
diagnoses.description: A mental health disorder characterized by persistently depressed mood or loss of interest in activities, causing significant impairment in daily life. Fatigue is a common symptom, and there can be a psychosomatic component to other symptoms like restless legs syndrome. Additionally, the stress and impact on the immune system can predispose someone to infections, including vaginitis.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition that causes pain all over the body. Symptoms include severe fatigue and sleep problems, which can contribute to the sensation of restless legs. The systemic impact of fibromyalgia might indirectly affect the occurrence of vaginitis.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. The fatigue worsens with physical or mental activity but doesn't improve with rest. Restless legs syndrome may be a comorbid condition, both contributing to the sense of fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, life-threatening allergic reaction that can occur suddenly and affect the whole body.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic condition causing severe swelling in various parts of the body, potentially triggered by stress or injury.

diagnoses.name: Acute Allergic Conjunctivitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory response of the eye's conjunctiva triggered by allergens, causing redness and swelling.

diagnoses.name: Food Poisoning
diagnoses.description: Illness caused by consuming contaminated food, leading to gastrointestinal symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Chemical Poisoning
diagnoses.description: Exposure to toxic chemicals causing symptoms ranging from mild irritation to severe systemic effects.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Shock Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, life-threatening complication of certain bacterial infections, often associated with tampon use.

diagnoses.name: Acute Pancreatitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the pancreas causing severe abdominal pain and systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Acute Hepatitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the liver causing symptoms like jaundice, abdominal pain, and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Gastroenteritis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the stomach and intestines causing vomiting, diarrhea, and cramps.

diagnoses.name: Scombroid Poisoning
diagnoses.description: A foodborne illness typically resulting from improperly stored or preserved fish, leading to histamine poisoning.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction that can occur rapidly. Symptoms can include angioedema, vomiting, and hypoxia.

diagnoses.name: Food Poisoning
diagnoses.description: Illness caused by consuming contaminated food. Common symptoms include vomiting, abdominal cramps, and sometimes hypoxia due to severe dehydration.

diagnoses.name: Gastroenteritis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the stomach and intestines typically caused by a viral or bacterial infection. Symptoms include vomiting and abdominal cramps.

diagnoses.name: Norovirus Infection
diagnoses.description: A highly contagious virus causing inflammation of the stomach and intestines. Symptoms include vomiting, abdominal cramps, and sometimes low oxygen levels due to dehydration.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Reaction
diagnoses.description: A reaction by the immune system to a substance that is not normally harmful. Symptoms can include rhinorrhea, angioedema, and in severe cases, hypoxia.

diagnoses.name: Asthma Attack
diagnoses.description: A sudden worsening of asthma symptoms due to the tightening of muscles around the airways. Symptoms can include hypoxia and, in some cases, vomiting from severe coughing.

diagnoses.name: Acute Pancreatitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the pancreas that can cause abdominal pain, vomiting, and hypoxia due to complications.

diagnoses.name: Cholera
diagnoses.description: An acute diarrheal illness caused by infection of the intestine. In severe cases, can lead to vomiting, severe dehydration, and hypoxia.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety or Panic Attack
diagnoses.description: Sudden episodes of intense fear or panic. Symptoms can include hyperventilation (leading to hypoxia), abdominal distress, and, in some cases, vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic condition characterized by recurrent episodes of severe swelling (angioedema). Symptoms can occasionally include abdominal cramps and, in severe cases, airway obstruction leading to hypoxia.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by recurrent attacks of moderate to severe throbbing and pulsating pain on one side of the head. The aura includes visual disturbances and other neurological symptoms that appear before the headache and last for about 20 to 60 minutes.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells start to die in minutes. Symptoms can include sudden numbness, confusion, trouble seeing, walking, and a severe headache.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a ministroke, a TIA is a brief period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke, such as numbness and headache, but typically lasts only a few minutes and usually causes no permanent damage.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Its symptoms depend on the size, type, and location. Symptoms can include headaches, seizures, vomiting, difficulty speaking, and sensory changes like numbness.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. Symptoms include numbness, impairment of speech, severe fatigue, dizziness, and problems with coordination and balance.

diagnoses.name: Intracerebral Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: Occurs when a blood vessel inside the brain bursts and leaks blood into the surrounding brain tissue. It's a cause of stroke, and symptoms may include a sudden severe headache, vomiting, vision changes, numbness or paralysis, and difficulty swallowing.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the fluid and membranes surrounding your brain and spinal cord. Meningitis can lead to symptoms such as fever, vomiting, intense headache, light sensitivity, stiff neck, and confusion.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A collection of pus that develops in the brain due to an infection or trauma. Symptoms can include headache, fever, vomiting, confusion, seizures, and neurological deficits such as numbness.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness. Headache and postictal confusion are common after a seizure.

diagnoses.name: Hypertensive Brain Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: This occurs when high blood pressure causes small arteries inside the brain to burst. It leads to the bleeding inside the brain, causing symptoms like sudden severe headache, nausea or vomiting, numbness, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease commonly presents with leukopenia, proteinuria (due to kidney involvement), and nasal ulcers. Skin manifestations like lichen planus and neuropsychiatric symptoms including delirium can also occur.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: A group of disorders that involve inflammation of the blood vessels. Symptoms can vary but may include skin conditions like lichen planus, renal issues manifesting as proteinuria, and neurologic symptoms such as delirium. Nasal ulcers could suggest a specific type like Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.rationale: An inflammatory condition known for muscle weakness and distinctive skin rashes, which could be confused with or accompany lichen planus. It may also lead to systemic symptoms including leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This disease shows overlapping symptoms of multiple autoimmune disorders including SLE, with possible manifestations like proteinuria, leukopenia, and various skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily affecting joints, it can present systemic symptoms including leukopenia and skin manifestations that might resemble lichen planus. Secondary Sjögren's syndrome can cause nasal ulcers.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: An inflammatory disease that can affect multiple organs, including the skin, presenting lesions similar to lichen planus, and possibly affecting the kidneys (proteinuria) and causing leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout your body, leading to symptoms including mouth and nasal ulcers. Skin lesions and systemic symptoms are also possible.

diagnoses.name: Lupus Nephritis
diagnoses.rationale: A specific condition related to SLE focusing on kidney involvement, presenting with significant proteinuria, potential leukopenia, and other systemic symptoms reflecting SLE.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Hepatitis
diagnoses.rationale: Liver inflammation over a prolonged period can lead to leukopenia due to splenomegaly, and potentially contribute to skin conditions including lichen planus.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.rationale: HIV can cause a wide variety of symptoms depending on the phase of the disease, including leukopenia (as a part of generalized immune suppression), oral ulcers, and renal complications such as proteinuria. Skin conditions like lichen planus might also be more common in HIV-positive patients.
